ickSort or Merge Sort on modern hardware, even though they share the same theoretical time complexity. If you need blazing performance on real-world data, or if you’re sorting structures where preserving relative order matters, Heap Sort isn’t the hero—there are faster, smoother tools. And if your environment allows recursion, extra memory, or stable sorting, then Merge Sort or TimSort will leave Heap Sort sitting in the dust.","position":{"start":{"line":445,"column":1},"end":{"line":445,"column":1}},"key":"x5ap1AWwn1"}],"key":"b1SmydPDeg"}],"key":"xYbPIyPBEf"}],"key":"aWKUTQlvkU"},"references":{"cite":{"order":[],"data":{}}},"footer":{"navigation":{"prev":{"title":"Quicksort - Linked Lists","url":"/xquicksortlinkedlists","group":"CSCI 132"},"next":{"title":"Understanding Three Quick, Merge, and Heap Sort Algorithms","url":"/xunderstandingquickmergeheap","group":"CSCI 132"}}},"domain":"http://localhost:3002"}